    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>From <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/tooldocs/windows/jar.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">the docs</a>:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>To extract the files from a jar file, use <code>x</code>, as in:</p>\n\n<pre><code>C:\\Java&gt; jar xf myFile.jar\n</code></pre>\n  \n  <p>To extract only certain files from a jar file, supply their filenames:</p>\n\n<pre><code>C:\\Java&gt; jar xf myFile.jar foo bar\n</code></pre>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The folder where <code>jar</code> is probably isn't <code>C:\\Java</code> for you, on my Windows partition it's:</p>\n\n<pre><code>C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Java\\jdk[some_version_here]\\bin\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Unless the location of <code>jar</code> is in your path environment variable, you'll have to specify the full path/run the program from inside the folder.</p>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT:</strong> Here's another article, specifically focussed on extracting JARs: <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/deployment/jar/unpack.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/deployment/jar/unpack.html</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 284109,
      "reputation" : 47819,
      "user_id" : 581994,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 57,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d2ae9ac6fb51918297a0ce5dada0eb22?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Hot Licks",
